    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation to the author's intent in his canonical and historical context. Genesis 43 is not primarily a story about famine management or Egyptian court customs; it is a carefully orchestrated movement in the Bible's most extended exploration of sin, suffering, divine sovereignty, and familial reconciliation. The four movements below trace the chapter's argument from the domestic crisis in Canaan through the feast that closes the chapter, attending to how each pericope advances both the narrative and the theological argument.",
