        "excerpt": "And may God Almighty grant you compassion in the sight of the man, so that he will release to you your other brother and Benjamin. And as for me, if I am bereaved of my children, I am bereaved.",
        "body": "Jacob's instructions in verses 11-13 are the practical wisdom of a man who has not yet fully surrendered but is being moved toward it. He doubles the money (anticipating the accusation of theft), selects the finest products of Canaan (politeness before power), and names the steps in order. This is not unbelief; it is the responsible stewardship of a man who knows that trusting God does not mean ignoring prudence. The preparations of verses 11-13 and the prayer of verse 14 belong together — responsible action and dependent prayer are not alternatives in the biblical worldview.\n\nThe theological weight falls on the divine name Jacob chooses: El Shaddai. This is the name under which God appeared to Abraham and established the covenant of circumcision (17:1), the name Isaac invoked when blessing Jacob (28:3), the name God used when He appeared to Jacob at Bethel and renewed the Abrahamic covenant with him specifically (35:11). When Jacob prays 'May God Almighty grant you compassion,' he is not invoking a generic deity but the specific God of specific covenant promises made to his specific family. He is placing the journey within the trajectory of divine faithfulness that stretches back three generations. This is prayer as historical memory — recalling what God has done as the basis for what he is asking God to do.\n\nThe word *racham* (compassion, 43:14) is the Hebrew root for the deep, womb-like love of a mother for the child of her body (cf. Isaiah 49:15). Jacob is asking the God of covenant to grant the brothers the kind of love from this Egyptian official that a mother has for her child — an impossible request, humanly speaking, and therefore a God-sized one. The closing clause — 'if I am bereaved of my children, I am bereaved' — has the feel of a man landing on bedrock. Jonathan Edwards, in his analysis of Abraham's offering of Isaac, speaks of 'the faith that has been tried to the uttermost, which no longer calculates outcomes but rests in the character of the One who ordains them.' Jacob has reached that resting place. His 'if I am bereaved' is not despair; it is the same trust that says 'though He slay me, yet will I trust Him' (Job 13:15).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *El Shaddai* — the etymology is disputed (mountain-God, or God-who-is-sufficient, from *shadah*), but the canonical usage is consistent: the name of God's covenant-power over human impossibility. *Racham* (compassion) — from *rechem* (womb); the visceral, relational, irreversible love of one bound to another by the bonds of new life. *Shakhol* (bereaved, 43:14, repeated) — the specific word for a parent who has lost a child; Jacob uses it doubled, as if to say: even the worst that can be named is within the sovereignty of El Shaddai."
